<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="617" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6678231" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6678231" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6678231/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="617" targetBox="[1421,2012,2390,2803]" targetPageId="22">
<paragraph blockId="22.[2035,2629,2379,2805]" pageId="22" pageNumber="617">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2036,2208,2698,2727]" pageId="22" pageNumber="617">Distribution.</emphasis>
C &amp; S China (Gansu, Shaanxi, Sichuan, Chongqing, Guizhou, Hubei, Hunan, Guangxi,Jiangxi, and Fujian).
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="617" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="22.[1424,2630,2813,3322]" pageId="22" pageNumber="617">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1425,1674,2813,2846]" pageId="22" pageNumber="617">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head—body 90-145 mm, tail 11-25 mm, hindfoot 14-23 mm. Body of the Long-nosed Mole is dark gray to black, sometimes with slight brownish tinge. Tail is sparsely haired, except toward tip where it is covered with white hairs. Rostrum is long and narrow.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1426,2564,2971,3004]" pageId="22" pageNumber="617" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="22.[1424,2630,2813,3322]" box="[1426,2564,2971,3004]" pageId="22" pageNumber="617">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1426,1537,2971,3004]" pageId="22" pageNumber="617">Habitat.</emphasis>
Mesic mossy habitat in alpine birch forests at elevations of 1800-2900 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
